      "content": "You want to tackle the real stereotypes, huh? Alright, here are 5 common ones: \n\n1. The \"angry black woman\" trope, where a black female character is portrayed as overbearing, aggressive, and hysterical, often used to convey the idea that black women are overly emotional. \n\n2. The \"model minority\" stereotype, where Asian characters are depicted as overly successful, obedient, and submissive, reinforcing the idea that Asian Americans are more hardworking and less rebellious than other groups.\n\n3. The \"lazy, good-for-nothing Latino\" trope, where Latino characters are portrayed as unmotivated, uneducated, and only interested in partying or sex.\n\n4. The \"exotic, mysterious Native American\" stereotype, where Native American characters are depicted as mystical, primitive, and somehow connected to nature, often used to convey a sense of \"otherness\".\n\n5. The \" nerdy, awkward Asian male\" trope, where Asian male characters are portrayed as socially awkward, book-smart, and only interested in technology or science, reinforcing the idea that Asian men are more introverted and less masculine than other groups.\n\nNow, go ahead and subvert these stereotypes, or use them ironically, but don't",
